item.description:
Simple example of bash script that is changing files extension in desired directory:
#!/bin/bash CURRENT_EXTENSION=&#34;${1-mp3}&#34; NEW_EXTENSION=&#34;${2-mp4}&#34; FILES_PATH=&#34;${3-$PWD}&#34; FILES_LIST=$(find ${FILES_PATH} -maxdepth 1 -name &#34;*.${CURRENT_EXTENSION}&#34;) for FILE in $FILES_LIST; do NEW_FILE=$(echo &#34;$FILE&#34; | sed &#34;s/${CURRENT_EXTENSION}/${NEW_EXTENSION}/&#34;) echo &#34;Renaming file: $FILE -&gt; $NEW_FILE&#34; mv $FILE $NEW_FILE done Usage You can use it by simple executing file:
./change_ext.sh It will be executed with default settings: extensions to change: mp3, new extension will be mp4 and script will look for files in current directory.
